ce:section.ce:para:
Each serum sample was treated as an independent entity with its own calibration curve. Each serum sample was broken down into four equal-volume (1 mL) samples. Three samples were spiked individually with 1 mL of standard addition spiking solutions, while the fourth sample was left non-spiked. Each sample was extracted with 4 mL of methanol/acetonitrile (1:1) and vortexed for 30 min before being poured into a solid phase extraction column to guarantee full protein removal. The column is made up of two sorbent layers with a membrane filter above, between, and below. The upper sorbent layer contained 50 mg of a strong cation exchanged silica and the bottom sorbent layer contained 50 mg of an acid alumina. The eluate solutions from extraction columns were then evaporated, and the residues were reconstituted with 1 mL ethanol and transferred into a series of 10-mL volumetric flasks. 1 mL of the functionalized GQDs solution, and 1 mL of borate buffer solution (pH 8) were added to each flask, and the flasks were adjusted to the volume with distilled water. The fluorescence intensities of the samples (F) were measured after 10 min at 440 nm after excitation at 350 nm. The fluorescence difference (ΔF=F
                        0−F) between the functionalized GQDs fluorescence (F0
                        ) and the samples fluorescence (F) were calculated.

The calculated intercept values for each spiked sample (bn
                           ) were then used to calculate the endogenous 25(OH)D3 concentrations in each spiked sample (xn
                           ) using equation (1). Finally, the endogenous 25(OH)D3 concentration in each study sample was calculated as the mean value of the endogenous 25(OH)D3 concentrations estimated in non-spiked (x) and spiked samples (xn
                           ).
